setwd('~/Dropbox/Projects/da/eda/lesson5')
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
theme_set(theme_fivethirtyeight(12))
## Warning: New theme missing the following elements: panel.margin.x,
## panel.margin.y
pf <- read.delim('pseudo_facebook.tsv')
# Histograms of friend counts by gender
ggplot(aes(x = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), binwidth=25) +
  geom_histogram() +
  scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0, 1000),
                     breaks=seq(0, 1000, 50)) +
  facet_wrap(~gender)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

# Boxplots of friend counts by gender with mean friend count marked
ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = age),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom='point', shape=4)

# Median friend counts vs age, by gender
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender))) +
  geom_line(aes(color=gender), stat='summary', fun.y=median)

# Create dataframe of mean & median friend counts
# by age and gender
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
pf.fc_by_age_gender <- pf %>%
  filter(!is.na(gender)) %>% 
  group_by(age, gender) %>%
  summarize(mean_friend_count=mean(friend_count),
            median_friend_count=median(friend_count),
            n=n())

head(pf.fc_by_age_gender)

## Groups: age [3]

Thinking in Ratios

Wide and Long Format

Reshaping Data

Notes:

# install.packages('reshape2')
library(reshape2)

# Reshape long data to flat, spliting the gender data
# to respective female & male columns
pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <-
  dcast(pf.fc_by_age_gender,
        age ~ gender,
        value.var = 'median_friend_count')

head(pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide)
##   age female  male
## 1  13  148.0  55.0
## 2  14  224.0  92.5
## 3  15  276.0 106.5
## 4  16  258.5 136.0
## 5  17  245.5 125.0
## 6  18  243.0 122.0
# Alternatively, use dply and tidyr
library(tidyr)
pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <-
  subset(pf.fc_by_age_gender[c('age', 'gender', 'median_friend_count')],
         !is.na(gender)) %>% 
    spread(gender, median_friend_count) %>% 
    mutate(ratio = female / male)

head(pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide)
## Source: local data frame [6 x 4]
## 
##     age female  male    ratio
##   (int)  (dbl) (dbl)    (dbl)
## 1    13  148.0  55.0 2.690909
## 2    14  224.0  92.5 2.421622
## 3    15  276.0 106.5 2.591549
## 4    16  258.5 136.0 1.900735
## 5    17  245.5 125.0 1.964000
## 6    18  243.0 122.0 1.991803

Third Quantitative Variable

Notes:

pf$year_joined <- floor(2014 - pf$tenure / 365)

Cut a Variable

Notes:

summary(pf$year_joined)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    2005    2012    2012    2012    2013    2014       2
table(pf$year_joined)
## 
##  2005  2006  2007  2008  2009  2010  2011  2012  2013  2014 
##     9    15   581  1507  4557  5448  9860 33366 43588    70
?cut

# cutting year joined into the following bins
# (2004-2009]
# (2009-2011]
# (2011-2012]
# (2012-2014]

pf$year_joined.bucket <- cut(pf$year_joined,
                             breaks=c(2004, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014))

Plotting it All Together

Notes:

table(pf$year_joined.bucket, useNA = 'ifany')
## 
## (2004,2009] (2009,2011] (2011,2012] (2012,2014]        <NA> 
##        6669       15308       33366       43658           2
# Age vs friend count for each year joined bucket
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat ='summary', fun.y = median)

Plot the Grand Mean

Notes: Against the means of each bucket

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat ='summary', fun.y = mean) +
  geom_line(stat='summary', fun.y = mean, linetype = 2)

Bias-Variance Tradeoff Revisited

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = 'summary',
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 30 * round(tenure / 30), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 90 * round(tenure / 90), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = year_joined.bucket))

# Creates a new variable called all.purchases,
# which gives the total counts of yogurt for
# each observation or household.
yo <- transform(yo, all.purchases = strawberry + blueberry +
                    pina.colada + plain + mixed.berry)

Prices over Time

Notes: Price seems to be going up over time, with more frequent discounted prices, perhaps due to coupons or promos

qplot(x = all.purchases, data = yo, binwidth = 1,
     fill = I('#099DD9'))

ggplot(yo, aes(time, price)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = 1/4, shape= 21, fill = I('#F79420'))

Sampling Observations

Notes: It was difficult to get a sense of the price trajectory over time for households with infrequent purchases, but those households with a significant sample size showed an upward trend towards more expensive yogurts purchased.

Looking at Samples of Households

set.seed(5194)
sample.ids <- sample(levels(yo$id), 16)

ggplot(subset(yo, id %in% sample.ids), aes(time, price)) +
  facet_wrap(~id) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(aes(size=all.purchases), pch = 1)

Heat Maps

Notes:

# melt the data in long format
library(reshape2)
nci.long.samp <- melt(as.matrix(nci[1:200,]))
names(nci.long.samp) <- c("gene", "case", "value")
head(nci.long.samp)
##   gene case  value
## 1    1    1  0.300
## 2    2    1  1.180
## 3    3    1  0.550
## 4    4    1  1.140
## 5    5    1 -0.265
## 6    6    1 -0.070
# make the heat map
ggplot(aes(y = gene, x = case, fill = value),
  data = nci.long.samp) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = colorRampPalette(c("blue", "red"))(100))
